		</table></td><td class="PanelBodyAlternate" valign="Top"><table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="3" border="0" width="100%">
			<tr>
				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Comment<a name="42130"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">May 25 04 2:53 PM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span><blockquote><b>Quote:</b><br><span class="quote">I'm always surprised by the amount of hostility people have for SoE. If you don't like their games, why are you reading the boards about them? It just totally amazes me that people who dislike something so much stilll pay so much attention to what happens.</span></blockquote>
<br />

<br />
I know I probably come across &quot;hostile&quot; but that is not the case at all actually.  I am simply a VERY harsh critic when it comes to video games, ALL video games.  I've been playing this stuff on various platforms since Nintendo was first released and I have seen alot of kick a$ games and <i>alot more</i> bad ones.
<br />

<br />
When I see a bad game, or bad game mechanic, or a nerf I don't agree with I can be pretty vocal.  That doesn't necessarily mean I think the entire game blows a$.
<br />

<br />
Take EQ for example.  When I first started the game it was pretty cool, there were a variety of things to occupy your time, quests seemed more worthwhile because the reward was commensurate with the effort AND getting help for them wasn't like pulling teeth.  Leveling wasn't quite the &quot;chore&quot; because you knew the max level, each level was more significant, and a &quot;fully experienced&quot; toon was actually obtainable by a mortal human in a timely fashion.  Faction was a part of the game.  Oh, did I mention there were no shitty bugs (collision, mobs/players halfway in the floor, stuck characters, etc)?
<br />

<br />
And then it slowly went downhill IMO.
<br />

<br />
They stopped building on those fundamentals and proceeded to add mass amounts of pure upward content.  Quests that <i>were</i> added weren't commensurate with the reward because of the tediousness - you'd have to give up your first born child to get help with them.  Levels/AA were added and the player base was spread out even more, railroading everyone into their &quot;main&quot;.  Which consequently went well with the &quot;40 new zones in XYZ expansion!&quot; that would remain unpopulated because normal people can barely keep one toon &quot;current&quot; (keys, flags, gear, levels/AA) let alone play an alt.  Faction, what's that?  Items became less and less individual with the &quot;all/all&quot; tags being slapped on everything.
<br />

<br />
Still, some things sucked in the beginning and got better.  Tradeskills, travel, buffs (Buff circle + camp to the chat room for Naggy!), less crowding in experience zones, soulbinders, graveyards, bazaar.
<br />

<br />

<br />
Anyway, the exact reason I am particularily harsh with respect to EQ is because the game has the potential to be made better, but seemingly isn't.  To use the baseball example above..  it's like hiring a professional baseball player to play on your team.  You are going to expect some pretty outstanding play, right?  He IS a professional after all..  What happens when the guy goes out and bats .100 for the year?
<br />

<br />
You're going to ask what the h*ll is going on!  If the player seems receptive you may try to help him improve, if not you'll dump him.
<br />

<br />
IMO, that's how people have tried to approach EQ.  At the very least we expect the game makers to be professional, no?  This would probably include making sure the game is bug free.  Given the job description, that wouldn't be anymore unfair than expecting a baseball player to know the rules of the game.  How about knowing the fundamentals of what makes a good game?  Any true video game fan would probably know these, as any true baseball player would know the fundamentals of what makes a winning team.  How about creativity?  That, I suppose is the trickiest part of making a video game, much like being successful in baseball (high batting average, on-base percentage, etc) it comes and goes.  But like any baseball player will tell you, practice the fundamentals and the rest will fall in line.
<br />

<br />
What does all this rambling mean?  Well, I don't know about everyone else but it seems to me that, at the very least, EQ is not made by video game fans.  <img src="/skins/default/images/emotions/emotion-8.gif" border="0" alt="Expressionless" hspace="2" /></span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="SmallText"><hr size="1" align="left" width="15%">Lexicus Magnavin - 65 Maestro</span></td>
